Homework Description

I have chosen 4 datasets and will try to make predictions with 4 different approaches. Then compare them and try to explain which properties of the datasets affected the performance of the different algorithms and what specific modifications were needed for different approaches

DATASET 1:

Student Performance
Web Page

Dataset has personal and grades data of students from math and portuguese language courses. We will be only using Portuguese grades of the students. To make things harder we will not use the other exam grades of the students but we will only focus on personal information about students.

Dataset has multiclass, binary and continuous attributes. We will approach the dataset with regression.

DATASET 2:

Breast Cancer
Web Page

This breast cancer databases was obtained from the University of Wisconsin Hospitals, Madison from Dr. William H. Wolberg.

We have medical information about the cell with anomaly. All attributes except the target one is continuous. We will approach the dataset with classification: Malign or Benign.

DATASET 3:

Online News Popularity
Web Page

This dataset contains many continuous and binary attributes. We will try to predict the number of shares the article will get via regression.

DATASET 4:

Polish Companies Bankruptcy
Web Page

This dataset contains all continuous attributes about companies and their status. (Bankrupted or Not)

    mutate(MServices = ifelse(Mjob == 'services', 1, 0)) %>% 
    mutate(MOther = ifelse(Mjob == 'other', 1, 0)) %>% 
    mutate(MAthome = ifelse(Mjob == 'at_home', 1, 0))  %>% 
    mutate(FTeacher = ifelse(Fjob == 'teacher', 1, 0)) %>% 
    mutate(FHealth = ifelse(Fjob == 'health', 1, 0)) %>% 
    mutate(FServices = ifelse(Fjob == 'services', 1, 0)) %>% 
    mutate(FOther = ifelse(Fjob == 'other', 1, 0)) %>% 
    mutate(FAthome = ifelse(Fjob == 'at_home', 1, 0))  %>% 
    # reasonhome reasonreputation reasoncourse reasonother

Random Forest

For random forest well be tuning mtry and splitrule. Choosing m as the square root of all features or log_2 of all features is advised. So well be around these numbers. As we are dealing with a regression data our split rule will be variance and extratrees.

set.seed(1)
# choosing m=sqrt(# all features) or m=log_2(#all features) may be a good starting point
grid_rf_1=expand.grid(mtry = c(5, 7, 9, 13),
                    splitrule = c("variance","extratrees"),
                    min.node.size = c(5))

rf_fit_1 <- train(G1 ~ ., data = data_train_1,
                 method = "ranger", 
                 trControl = fit_control,
                 num.trees=500,
                 tuneGrid = grid_rf_1)

Test

Note that the performance values weve seen were the results only from training data. Now we will test them on our test data.

First, we create a function for calculating MSE (Ive then realized theres a built in one)

# create a function for calculating MSE
mse_calculate <- function(pred,real){
    return <- mean((pred-real)^2)
}
pred_pra_1 <- predict(pra_fit_1, data_test_1)
pred_dt_1 <- predict(dt_fit_1_30, data_test_1)
pred_rf_1 <- predict(rf_fit_1, data_test_1)
pred_gbm_1 <- predict(gbm_fit_1, data_test_1)
mse_pra_1 <- mse_calculate(pred_pra_1, data_test_1$G1)
mse_dt_1 <- mse_calculate(pred_dt_1, data_test_1$G1)
mse_rf_1 <- mse_calculate(pred_rf_1, data_test_1$G1)
mse_gbm_1 <- mse_calculate(pred_gbm_1, data_test_1$G1)

MSE_1 <- data.table(mse_pra_1,mse_dt_1,mse_rf_1,mse_gbm_1)
MSE_1
mse_pra_1 mse_dt_1 mse_rf_1 mse_gbm_1
5.583059 6.302627 5.250776 5.458759

We can see that: Random forest has the least error, then gradient bossting follows it with a similar error result to penalized regression. Decision tree performed much worse then the others.

Also all errors in the training data was half the ones in the test data. So our models probably over fitted a little.

#function for calculating accuracy
accuracy_calculate <- function(pred,real){
    return(nrow(real[real$V2==pred,])/nrow(real))
}

#predciting test data

We need to handle NAs and ?s in the data first. I will replace missing values with the columns mean. Also recall that this dataset is highly imbalanced. So we will need to take some more actions.

custom_func <- function(x) {
  return (ifelse(x=='?',NA,as.numeric(x)))
}
#turn elements from char to doubles and ? to NA

suppressWarnings(for(i in 1:ncol(data_4)){
  data_4[is.na(data_4[,i]), i] <- mean(data_4[,i], na.rm = TRUE)
})
